data.body:
On the `develop3d` branch, I am currently unable to add to the `Window.ClientSizeChanged` event handler, and the problem may extend to the other `Window` event handlers. When I add an event, there is no compile or runtime errors. But changing the window size does not trigger the event.

Currently, `Window` is of type `GameWindow`. If I replace this type with `OpenTKGameWindow`, then it seems to work. That is, if I replace (`Game.cs`, Line 307)

``` csharp
public GameWindow Window
{
    get { return Platform.Window; }
}
```

with

``` csharp
public OpenTKGameWindow Window
{
    get { return (OpenTKGameWindow)Platform.Window; }
}
```

then changing window size once again triggers the `ClientSizeChanged` events.

A proper fix probably requires a better solution (or at least some preprocessors to isolate the OpenTK platforms), but I wanted to mention the issue.
[Edited for clarification]

If you embed the GameWindow into a subview of the main application window the mouse position is calculated incorrectly.
To fix this you simply need to update the [SetMousePosition](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/MacOS/GameWindow.cs#L739-743) function in GameWindow to this...

``` C#
private void SetMousePosition (PointF location)
{
    var locationInView = ConvertPointFromView (location, null);
    Mouse.SetPosition ((int)locationInView.X, (int)(ClientBounds.Height - locationInView.Y));
}
```

Passing null as the second parameter to ConvertPointFromView calculates the coordinates in the view from the base coordinates that are retrieved from the LocationInView property of the mouse event. See the [NSView documentation](https://developer.apple.com/library/mac/#documentation/Cocoa/Reference/ApplicationKit/Classes/nsview_Class/Reference/NSView.html#//apple_ref/occ/instm/NSView/convertPoint:fromView:) for more info.
